### Details
ILSpy version 9.1.0.7988+03b7444943e720b3134d296c0c8dd3876f8ea4ce

Since the local in the caller is unused, I think it might as well decompile to `f(out _, out _);`, which recompiles to different IL but should have the same semantics? C# disallows the callee from attempting to read from out parameters, but IL does nothing to prevent the callee from `ldind` on the out parameter. ECMA-335 mentions that the CLI does not enforce the semantics of `[out]` but can use it for optimization.
Perhaps try to decompile to discards? Or perhaps gate it behind a setting flag?

